Question d: part 1

OLS_m1=lm(cases_log~v2x_polyarchy, data=Corona)

summary(OLS_m1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = cases_log ~ v2x_polyarchy, data = Corona)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -2.31471 -0.69695 -0.00291  0.79433  2.83502 
## 
## Coefficients:
##               Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)     1.9619     0.2034   9.646  < 2e-16 ***
## v2x_polyarchy   1.4940     0.3450   4.330 2.61e-05 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.091 on 161 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1043, Adjusted R-squared:  0.09876 
## F-statistic: 18.75 on 1 and 161 DF,  p-value: 2.608e-05
ggplot(data = Corona,  aes(x = v2x_polyarchy , y = cases_log)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.4, color = "maroon") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, formula = y ~ x)+
  labs(x= "electoral democracy", y= "Corona cases", title= "xxxxx")

When I estimate the model of cases_log and v2x_polyarchy I first look at the summary of the OLS I made. I am interested in the parameters \(\beta\) 1 and \(\beta\) 0. \(\beta\) 0 is the intercept, and I can see that this is 1.9619. \(\beta\) 1 is the slope or steepness and I can see that this is 1.4940. This corresponds to the regression line I put in the scatterplot. The regression line shows a slope upwards, meaning that if electoral democracy increases by one unit, the log of corona cases increases by 1.4940. I can conclude from this that the more electoral a democracy gets, the more corona cases can be found.

Question d: part 2

OLS_m1=lm(cases_log~v2x_libdem, data=Corona)

summary(OLS_m1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = cases_log ~ v2x_libdem, data = Corona)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -2.32986 -0.67076  0.06097  0.79488  2.77711 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   2.0592     0.1605  12.828  < 2e-16 ***
## v2x_libdem    1.6922     0.3302   5.125 8.44e-07 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.069 on 161 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1402, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1349 
## F-statistic: 26.26 on 1 and 161 DF,  p-value: 8.441e-07
ggplot(data = Corona,  aes(x = v2x_libdem , y = cases_log)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.4, color = "maroon") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, formula = y ~ x)

\(\beta\) 0 is the intercept, and I can see that this is 2.0592. \(\beta\) 1 is the slope or steepness and I can see that this is 1.6922. This corresponds to the regression line I put in the scatterplot. The regression line shows a slope upwards, meaning that if liberal democracy increases by one unit, the log of corona cases increases by 2.0592. I can conclude from this that the more liberal a democracy gets, the more corona cases can be found. This positive relation between liberal democracy and corona cases is even stronger than it was between electoral democracy and corona cases, which I concluded because the regression line (and thus also \(\beta\) 1) is steeper.
